SIMPLE: irritate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Irritate
<hw>Ir"ri*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See 1 st
<er>Irritant</er>.]</ety> <def>To render null and void.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Abp. Bramhall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Irritate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Irritate
<hw>Ir"ri*tate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Irritated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Irritating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>irritatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>irritare</ets>. Of doubtful
origin.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To increase the action or violence of; to heighten
excitement in; to intensify; to stimulate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cold maketh the spirits vigorous and <qex>irritateth</qex>
them.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To excite anger or displeasure in; to provoke; to
tease; to exasperate; to annoy; to vex; <as>as, the insolence of a
tyrant <ex>irritates</ex> his subjects</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dismiss the man, nor <qex>irritate</qex> the god:⟦br⟧
Prevent the rage of him who reigns above.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>To produce irritation in; to
stimulate; to cause to contract. See <er>Irritation</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To make morbidly excitable, or
oversensitive; to fret; <as>as, the skin is <ex>irritated</ex> by
friction; to <ex>irritate</ex> a wound by a coarse
bandage.</as></def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To fret; inflame; excite; provoke; tease; vex;
exasperate; anger; incense; enrage.</syn> <usage> -- To
<er>Irritate</er>, <er>Provoke</er>, <er>Exasperate</er>. These words
express different stages of excited or angry feeling.
<xex>Irritate</xex> denotes an excitement of quick and slightly angry
feeling which is only momentary; <as>as, <ex>irritated</ex> by a hasty
remark</as>. To <xex>provoke</xex> implies the awakening of some open
expression of decided anger; <as>as, a <ex>provoking</ex> insult</as>.
<xex>Exasperate</xex> denotes a provoking of anger at something
unendurable. Whatever comes across our feelings <xex>irritates</xex>;
whatever excites anger <xex>provokes</xex>; whatever raises anger to a
high point <xex>exasperates</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧Susceptible and nervous people
are most easily <xex>irritated</xex>; proud people are quickly
<xex>provoked</xex>; hot and fiery people are soonest
<xex>exasperated</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Crabb.</au></usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Irritate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Irritate
<hw>Ir"ri*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Excited;
heightened.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>irritated</ent>⟦br⟧
